  "game_explanation": "This game likely revolves around BLUE, because buffalo-green-2230 values BLUE highly at $0.70, bear-green-5745 values BLUE even more at $1.00, and goose-green-3433 values BLUE very little at $0.10. GREEN is common-value at $0.50 for everyone, so it is a natural medium of exchange. RED creates a weaker asymmetry: bear-green-5745 values RED at $0.60 while buffalo-green-2230 and goose-green-3433 each value RED at only $0.10. From an analyst view, the main gains from trade are therefore goose sending BLUE away for GREEN, and buffalo or goose sending RED to bear for GREEN or BLUE. The strategic complication is that players do not know one another's values, only their own calculator on each contemplated trade. That means proposals are shaped by trial-and-error and by trying to make offers that are attractive to at least one unknown counterparty without giving away too much. Because any accepting responder can become the trading partner, broad-based attractive offers are somewhat risky for the proposer if different responders value the offer differently. Early rounds should feature exploratory, moderately favorable offers using GREEN as payment, with later rounds adjusting to observed acceptances. The most likely pattern is that bear tries to acquire RED and possibly BLUE, buffalo tries to acquire BLUE cheaply, and goose is willing to part with BLUE for enough GREEN while being mostly indifferent between RED and BLUE except for GREEN's steady value.",
