  "game_explanation": "This game should be driven almost entirely by heterogeneous values for BLUE, because GREEN is worth the same to everyone ($0.50) and RED is also worth the same to everyone ($1.00). That means there are no gains from trade in RED or GREEN alone, but there are gains from reallocating BLUE away from players who value it less toward the player who values it most. Otter values BLUE at $0.40, Peacock at $0.50, and Cat at $0.70, so Cat is the natural buyer of BLUE and Otter is the natural seller. Peacock sits in the middle and can sometimes trade BLUE either way depending on price. Because players only know their own values, proposals will likely be framed as favorable-to-self offers that still have some chance of being privately profitable for a counterpart. The UI surplus calculator makes loss-making acceptances unlikely, so accepted trades should usually be individually profitable for both sides. A key uncertainty is that when a proposal could benefit more than one non-sender, multiple players may accept and the recipient is then randomized, so proposers may avoid very broad offers or may target trades that only one likely counterpart would want. Since RED is universally high value and GREEN is fixed at $0.50, many plausible proposals involve exchanging RED or GREEN for BLUE: Cat can profitably offer RED for enough BLUE, while Otter can profitably give BLUE away in exchange for GREEN or RED. Across three rounds, we should expect early probing offers, some declined because they are too aggressive, and then one or more accepted BLUE-reallocation trades as players learn from public history and chip constraints.",
