{
  "game_explanation": "This game is likely to revolve around red-for-blue exchange, with green mostly serving as a neutral fallback chip. From an analyst view, dog-blue-6080 values RED most highly ($1.00) and BLUE least among the two private colors ($0.20), so dog most wants to acquire RED and is relatively willing to give up BLUE. butterfly-blue-3807 is the mirror image in a softer form: butterfly values BLUE highly ($0.90) and RED moderately ($0.60), so butterfly most wants BLUE and can part with RED if the terms are favorable. ram-purple-9443 values both private colors weakly, especially BLUE ($0.10), and values GREEN at $0.50 like everyone else, so ram is the most likely liquidity provider: ram will often accept trades that convert BLUE into RED or GREEN, and may also offer BLUE to obtain GREEN. The main uncertainty is informational. Players do not know each other's values, only that red and blue lie somewhere in the public range. That means individually rational trades can fail if proposers ask for too much or target the wrong counterpart, and with simultaneous acceptance a proposer cannot choose which accepter receives the trade. Early rounds are therefore likely to feature cautious probes. Over time, observed acceptances reveal partial information: if butterfly accepts giving RED for BLUE, that suggests BLUE is attractive to butterfly; if ram accepts almost any BLUE-for-something trade, others may infer ram is weak on BLUE. Because all players begin symmetric in holdings and there are only three rounds, the game likely features a mix of one or two successful exploratory trades and several declined ambitious proposals rather than fully efficient reallocation.",
